title: Victoria Palace Theatre
description:
The Victoria Palace Theatre ( http://www.victoriapalacetheatre.org ) opened in 1832 as Moy's Music Hall but was demolished in 1886 with a new building being constructed on the same site. It was again demolished and re-opened in 1911 under its current name of the Victoria Palace Theatre. Over the century the theatre has hosted numerous exciting plays and musicals such as Me and My Girl in 1937 and The Little Foxes in 1982 starring Elizabeth Taylor. The smash-hit ballet-boy musical Billy Elliot opened at the Victoria Palace in 2005.

Home of Billy Elliot, the musical faithful to the film, with the addition of music by Elton John. When it was released in New York, it swept the year's Tony awards.

http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Billy_Elliot_the_Musical

BoxOffice: http://www.billyelliotthemusical.com/tickets/

title: Holy Trinity Sloane Street
description:
Holy Trinity Sloane Street (The Church of the Holy and Undivided Trinity with Saint Jude, Upper Chelsea, sometimes known as Holy Trinity Sloane Square) is a London Anglican parish church, built 1888-90 at the south-eastern side of Sloane Street to a striking Arts & Crafts design by the architect John Dando Sedding at the cost of the 5th Earl Cadogan, in whose London estate it lay. It replaced an earlier building only half its size which, at the time of its demolition, was less than sixty years old.

http://www.holytrinitysloanesquare.co.uk/

title: Peace Pagoda
description:
Buddhist stupa designed to provide a focus for people of all races and creeds to help unite them in their search for world peace. The Peace Pagoda was a gift to London from the
Japanese Buddhist Order, Nipponzan Myohoji, in 1985.

The London Peace Pagoda was completed in 1985 on the south side of the River Thames in Battersea Park, London. Permission to build it was the last legislative act of the Greater London Council.

title: Beaufoy Institute
description:
Listed Grade II building built by the Beaufoy family as part of the Lambeth Ragged Schools movement. Externally it is decorated with swags of fruit, plaques with the dates 1851 (the first school) and 1907 (Beaufoy Institute). Internally it has unique Cockerill-Doulton salt glaze tiles. The Beaufoy lay unused after the demise of of Inner London Education Authority in 1990. It was sold in 2013 to Diamond Way Buddhism UK (the car park at the rear was sold separately to Bellway Homes). The building is being refurbished and will open as a Buddhist centre in the Karma Kagyu lineage in April 2014.
See www.beaufoy-institute.org.

title: Apollo Victoria Theatre
description:
The Apollo Victoria Theatre ( http://www.apollovictoriatheatre.org ) is located in Victoria, London, and dates back to 1929 when it opened as a cinema. The building closed as a venue for film in 1975 and reopened as a theatre, basing itself on musical performances. Hosting musicals such as The Sound of Music and Starlight Express which ran for an incredible 18 years, the venue proved to be very popular for live theatre. In 2006, the musical Wicked opened at the Apollo Victoria.

http://www.apollovictoriatheatre.com/

title: St Philip's Church, Battersea
description:
St Philip's Church was built in the centre of St Philip Square as part of the Parktown Estate, a development laid out from 1865 onwards either side of Queenstown Road. St Philip Square was laid out in the early stages of the estate and surrounds the church on three sides. The church was designed by James Thomas Knowles & was built in 1870 in the centre of the square, set within a raised railed garden that is predominantly grass, with shrubs planted around the church, rose bed, seating and mature London plane trees. It's now being used by the Ethiopian Church.

http://debretsionlondon.org/
